TY  - JOUR
AU  - Frankel, David M.
AU  - Jin, Yu
T1  - Securitization and Lending Competition
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdv013
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 82
IS  - 4
SP  - 1383
EP  - 1408
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We study the effects of securitization on interbank lending competition. An applicant's observable features are seen by a remote bank, while her true credit quality is known only to a local bank. Without securitization, the remote bank does not compete because of a winner's curse. With securitization, in contrast, ignorance is bliss: the less a bank knows about its loans, the less of a lemons problem it faces in selling them. This enables the remote bank to compete successfully in the lending market. Consistent with the empirical evidence, remote and securitized loans default more than observationally equivalent local and unsecuritized loans, respectively.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdv013
ER  - 



